\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Per-category results for Claude Sonnet\nobreakspace  {}4.6 and EvoCUA-32B.} Audio-dependent categories (A, B, G) show the largest gains---from near-zero to 6--10/10. Visual-temporal categories (C, D, F) improve consistently. Category\nobreakspace  {}J (games) is the exception: real-time action latency, not perception, is the bottleneck. Category\nobreakspace  {}E (dashboard) shows minimal change for Claude because current values are visible in single screenshots.\relax }}{14}{figure.caption.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:percategory}{{6}{14}{\textbf {Per-category results for Claude Sonnet~4.6 and EvoCUA-32B.} Audio-dependent categories (A, B, G) show the largest gains---from near-zero to 6--10/10. Visual-temporal categories (C, D, F) improve consistently. Category~J (games) is the exception: real-time action latency, not perception, is the bottleneck. Category~E (dashboard) shows minimal change for Claude because current values are visible in single screenshots.\relax }{figure.caption.12}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Ablation: progressive contribution of each AOI component} (Claude Sonnet\nobreakspace  {}4.6). Inter-step keyframes provide +20\,pp (any selection method achieves this; see Table\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {tab:ablation}). ASR adds +6\,pp (directional; $p=0.18$ for this transition alone, Table\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {tab:ablation_stats}). Visual narration adds +18\,pp---the largest single-component gain; Section\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {sec:narration_discard} decomposes its mechanism. Error bars are approximate 95\% intervals using a symmetric Gaussian span (exact Wilson intervals in Table\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {tab:main}).\relax }}{14}{figure.caption.16}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:ablation}{{7}{14}{\textbf {Ablation: progressive contribution of each AOI component} (Claude Sonnet~4.6). Inter-step keyframes provide +20\,pp (any selection method achieves this; see Table~\ref {tab:ablation}). ASR adds +6\,pp (directional; $p=0.18$ for this transition alone, Table~\ref {tab:ablation_stats}). Visual narration adds +18\,pp---the largest single-component gain; Section~\ref {sec:narration_discard} decomposes its mechanism. Error bars are approximate 95\% intervals using a symmetric Gaussian span (exact Wilson intervals in Table~\ref {tab:main}).\relax }{figure.caption.16}{}}
\citation{qwen3vl}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Efficiency and cost across observation configurations on the 100-task benchmark for the five models with full instrumented runs. Grok-4 is excluded because its $\sim $80--180\,s/call latency floor distorts the cost/latency picture (Section\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {sec:grok}). Steps = mean steps per task (lower is better); Time = mean wall-clock per task; Lat.\ = total model inference latency per task; Obs = total observation processing time per task, including screenshot capture (${\sim }2$\,s/step) plus CLIP encoding, keyframe selection, and audio processing for AOI configurations. Tokens are accounted as input\nobreakspace  {}+\nobreakspace  {}output per task, estimated from the evaluation logs by \texttt  {experiments/compute\_tokens.py}: text at ${\sim }1.3$ tokens per word and a flat 258 tokens per image (Anthropic's vision-token approximation for downscaled screenshots; actual vision tokenization varies by provider). The same estimator is applied to every configuration, so relative comparisons are meaningful while absolute counts are approximate. \$\nobreakspace  {}/\nobreakspace  {}100 tasks computed from these estimates at May 2026 list prices: Claude\nobreakspace  {}Sonnet\nobreakspace  {}4.6 \$3/Mtok in, \$15/Mtok out; GPT-5.4 \$5/\$15; Gemini\nobreakspace  {}2.5\nobreakspace  {}Flash \$0.30/\$2.50; EvoCUA-32B and Fara-7B run locally. Despite per-step observation overhead, the AOI reduces \emph  {cost} by 15--50\% across the three cloud models (50\% on Claude, 15\% on GPT-5.4, 50\% on Gemini\nobreakspace  {}2.5\nobreakspace  {}Flash) because the step count drops more than the per-step input grows.\relax }}{15}{table.caption.14}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:efficiency}{{8}{15}{Efficiency and cost across observation configurations on the 100-task benchmark for the five models with full instrumented runs. Grok-4 is excluded because its $\sim $80--180\,s/call latency floor distorts the cost/latency picture (Section~\ref {sec:grok}). Steps = mean steps per task (lower is better); Time = mean wall-clock per task; Lat.\ = total model inference latency per task; Obs = total observation processing time per task, including screenshot capture (${\sim }2$\,s/step) plus CLIP encoding, keyframe selection, and audio processing for AOI configurations. Tokens are accounted as input~+~output per task, estimated from the evaluation logs by \texttt {experiments/compute\_tokens.py}: text at ${\sim }1.3$ tokens per word and a flat 258 tokens per image (Anthropic's vision-token approximation for downscaled screenshots; actual vision tokenization varies by provider). The same estimator is applied to every configuration, so relative comparisons are meaningful while absolute counts are approximate. \$~/~100 tasks computed from these estimates at May 2026 list prices: Claude~Sonnet~4.6 \$3/Mtok in, \$15/Mtok out; GPT-5.4 \$5/\$15; Gemini~2.5~Flash \$0.30/\$2.50; EvoCUA-32B and Fara-7B run locally. Despite per-step observation overhead, the AOI reduces \emph {cost} by 15--50\% across the three cloud models (50\% on Claude, 15\% on GPT-5.4, 50\% on Gemini~2.5~Flash) because the step count drops more than the per-step input grows.\relax }{table.caption.14}{}}
